The best approach is **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — a battle-tested NuGet package that wraps all of `System.IO` behind `IFileSystem`. No need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// Program.cs / Startup.cs
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

The mapping is straightforward — just prefix calls with `fileSystem.`:

| Before (static) | After (injected) |
|---|---|
| `File.ReadAllText(p)` | `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(p)` |
| `File.WriteAllText(p, c)` | `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(p, c)` |
| `Directory.Exists(p)` | `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(p)` |

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var service = new ConfigService(mockFs);

// ReadAllText works against in-memory files
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Load("/data/config.json"));

// WriteAllText writes to the mock
service.Save("/data/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/output.txt"));

// Directory.Exists checks the mock filesystem
Assert.True(service.EnsureDirectory("/data"));
Assert.False(service.EnsureDirectory("/nonexistent"));
```

No real disk I/O in tests — everything runs in memory, fast and deterministic.

> **Tip:** Once the packages are installed, you can use the `migrate-static-to-wrapper` skill to bulk-replace all `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites across your project mechanically. Just say the word.
